Additionally, [[Stan Lee]] makes a cameo as a school bus driver. {{WP|Winston Duke}} and {{WP|Florence Kasumba}} reprise their roles as [[M'Baku (Earth-199999)|M'Baku]] and [[Ayo (Earth-199999)|Ayo]], from ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'', respectively.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://lrmonline.com/news/this-black-panther-character-will-have-a-big-role-in-avengers-infinity-war/|title=This Black Panther Character Will Have A Big Role In Avengers: Infinity War|last=Medina|first=Joseph Jammer|work=LRM Online|date=6 February 2018|accessdate=1 March 2018}}<ref>[[:File:Marvel Studios' Avengers Infinity War - Official Trailer]]</ref> {{WP|Kerry Condon}} voices [[F.R.I.D.A.Y. (Earth-199999)|F.R.I.D.A.Y.]] {{WP|Jacob Batalon}}, {{WP|Tiffany Espensen}}, {{WP|Isabella Amara}}, and {{WP|Ethan Dizon}} reprise their roles as [[Edward Leeds (Earth-199999)|Ned Leeds]], [[Cindy Moon (Earth-199999)|Cindy Moon]], [[Sally Avril (Earth-199999)|Sally Avril]], and [[Brian McKeever (Earth-199999)|Tiny McKeever]], from ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]'', respectively.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://comicbook.com/marvel/2018/04/06/avengers-infinity-war-clip-spider-man-bus-marvel/|title= Spider-Man Swings Into Action in New 'Avengers: Infinity War' Clip|work= ComicBook.com|last= Anderson|first= Jenna|date= April 6, 2018|accessdate= April 8, 2018}}{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.blackfilm.com/read/2017/03/isabella-amara-talks-spider-man-homecoming-avengers-infinity-war/|title=Isabella Amara Talks About Her Casting In Spider-Man: Homecoming & Confirms Avengers: Infinity War Appearance|accessdate=16 July 2017|author=wilsonmorales|date=13 March 2017|work=blackfilm.com}} {{WP|Ross Marquand}} takes over the role of [[Johann Schmidt (Earth-199999)|Red Skull]], who was portrayed by {{WP|Hugo Weaving}} in ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]''. {{WP|Ameenah Kaplan}} portrays Gamora's mother. Michael Anthony Rogers and co-writer [[Stephen McFeely]] make cameos as Ross' aides.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://comicbook.com/marvel/2018/04/29/avengers-infinity-war-cameo-stephen-mcfeely-/|title= The Hidden 'Avengers: Infinity War' Cameo You Missed|work= ComicBook.com|last= Davis|first= Brandon|date= April 29, 2018|accessdate= May 31, 2018}} {{WP|Samuel L. Jackson}} and {{WP|Cobie Smulders}} make uncredited appearances in the post-credits scene as [[Nicholas Fury (Earth-199999)|Nick Fury]] and [[Maria Hill (Earth-199999)|Maria Hill]], respectively. One of the deleted scenes featured {{WP|Jon Favreau}} reprising his role as [[Harold Hogan (Earth-199999)|Happy Hogan]], along with co-director [[Joe Russo]] making a cameo appearance as a paparazzi photographer.

| Notes                   = * This film was announced during Marvel Studios' event at El Capitan Theatre on October 28, 2014.{{cite|ref=true|refname=Announcement|url=http://www.newsarama.com/22570-marvel-studios-event-live.html|title=Marvel Studios Event|work=Newsarama|first=Tom|last=McLean|date=28 October 2014|accessdate=28 October 2014}}
* Although ''Avengers: Infinity War - Part I'' was this film's original title, the Russo brothers subsequently confirmed that this film and ''Part II'' would be retitled to emphasize the differences between the two films.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/russo-brothers-confirm-avengers-infinity-war-title-change/|title=Russo Brothers Confirm: 'Avengers: Infinity War 1 And 2' Will Be Retitled|last=Ryan|first=Mike|work=Uproxx|date=4 May 2016|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref> The first part became simply ''Avengers: Infinity War'', while the second part had yet to be retitled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/marvel-surprise-avengers-infinity-war-wont-be-split-into-2-movies/|title=Marvel Surprise: ‚ÄòAvengers: Infinity War‚Äô Won‚Äôt Be Split Into 2 Movies|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|work=The Wrap|date=29 July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}} The second part's new title was revealed to be ''Avengers: Endgame'' on December 7, 2018 with the release of its first trailer.
* Filming for this film and ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' started on January 23, 2017, and wrapped on  July 14, 2017 for the former.{{cite|ref=true| first                   = Joseph| last                    = Schmidt| url                     = http://comicbook.com/marvel/2017/01/22/avengers-infinity-war-sequel-begin-filming/| title                   = Avengers: Infinity War And Sequel Set To Begin Filming Monday| work                    = ComicBook.com| date                    = 2017-01-22| accessdate              = 2017-01-24}}{{cite|ref=true|url= http://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/avengers-infinity-war-filming-ends/|title= Avengers: Infinity War has wrapped filming|work= EW|last= Romano|first= Nick|date= 2017-07-41|accessdate= 2018-01-12}}
* About two months before this film was set to release, its American premiere date was moved up one week, from May 4 to April 27, coinciding with its worldwide release.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/avengers-infinity-war-release-date-moves-april-1089951|title='Avengers: Infinity War' Release Date Moves Up One Week to April|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=1 March 2018|accessdate=1 March 2018}}
* For this film, [[Black Order (Earth-616)|Black Order]] member [[Black Dwarf (Earth-616)|Black Dwarf]] was adapted with the name "[[Cull Obsidian (Earth-199999)|Cull Obsidian]]." In the comics, "Cull Obsidian" is an alternative name for the Black Order.
* The official poster for this film contains two visual errors in it. The first is [[Thor Odinson (Earth-199999)|Thor]]'s scar being over the wrong eye (left instead of right), and the second is [[James Barnes (Earth-199999)|Bucky]]'s bionic arm not being fully transposed over his left arm (on the wrist).
* This film broke both the domestic opening weekend box office record and worldwide opening record with a $250 million domestic gross and $630 million worldwide, beating the records set by ''{{WP|Star Wars: The Force Awakens}}'' ($247.9 million) and ''{{WP|Fate of the Furious}}'' ($541.9 million), respectively.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4393&p=.htm|title='Avengers: Infinity War' Opens with Record Shattering $250M Domestically & $630M Worldwide|work=Box Office Mojo|first=Brad|last=Brevet|date=29 April 2018|accessdate=30 April 2018}}
** Additionally, this film broke the record for the fastest time a film managed to reach $1 billion at the worldwide box office, on its 11th day of release, again beating ''Star Wars: The Force Awakens'' which did so on its 12th day.{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/box-office-avengers-infinity-war-crossing-1b-record-time-1108547|title= Weekend Box Office: 'Avengers: Infinity War' Crosses $1B in Record Time|work= THR|last= McClintock|first= Pamela|date= May 4, 2018|accessdate= May 5, 2018}}
* This film became the 4th film in history to earn $2 billion in its worldwide box office gross, alongside ''Star Wars: The Force Awakens'', ''{{WP|Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic}}'', and ''{{WP|Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar}}''.{{cite|ref=true|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Worldwide Box Office Grosses|work= Box Office Mojo|accessdate= June 12, 2018}}
* With a worldwide total box office gross of $2 billion, this film became the highest-grossing film of 2018,{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2018&p=.htm|title= 2018 Yearly Box Office Results|accessdate= January 10, 2019|work= Box Office Mojo}} and at its peak the 4th-highest-grossing film of all time.{{cite|ref=true|url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title= All Time Worldwide Box Office|accessdate= January 10, 2019|work= Box Office Mojo|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190110152830/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|archivedate= January 10, 2019}}
| Trivia                  = * The release date of this film was around the time of the 10th Anniversary of the [[Earth-199999|Marvel Cinematic Universe]], which first appeared in {{sl|Iron Man (film)}}.
* With a running time of 2 hours and 29 minutes, this was, at the time of its release, the longest Marvel film.
* Writers [[Christopher Markus]] and [[Stephen McFeely]] toyed with the idea of introducing [[Nova|Richard Rider]] as the only surviving member of the [[Nova Corps (Earth-199999)|Nova Corps]] who would herald [[Thanos (Earth-199999)|Thanos]]' arrival instead of the [[Bruce Banner (Earth-199999)|Hulk]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/avengers-endgame-writers-suggested-x-men-storyline-marvel-1209732|title='Avengers: Endgame' Writers Share Ideas Abandoned Along the Way|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Aaron|last=Couch|date=11 May 2019|accessdate=22 May 2019}}
* An initial draft for this film included a reunion between [[Anthony Stark (Earth-199999)|Iron Man]] and [[Steven Rogers (Earth-199999)|Captain America]]. According to Stephen McFeely, the scene was scrapped because it meant slowing down the aspect of Thanos from the film.{{cite|ref=true|refname=Yahoo|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/captain-america-iron-man-scene-wasnt-6-things-didnt-know-avengers-infinity-war-165510777.html|title=7 things you didn't know about 'Avengers: Infinity War'|work=Yahoo! Entertainment|first=Kevin|last=Polowy|date=8 May 2018|accessdate=9 May 2018}}
* An early draft for this film had [[Samuel Wilson (Earth-199999)|Falcon]] go to space instead of [[Peter Parker (Earth-199999)|Spider-Man]].<ref name="Yahoo"/>
* In this film's French dub, Tony Stark insults [[Ebony Maw (Earth-199999)|Ebony Maw]] by calling him {{Wc|harrypotter|Tom Riddle|Voldemort}}, instead of {{Wc|spongebob|Squidward Tentacles|Squidward}}.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://comicbook.com/marvel/2018/04/30/avengers-infinity-war-harry-potter-voldemort-reference/|title='Avengers: Infinity War' Makes A Hilarious 'Harry Potter' Reference|work=Comicbook.com|first=Megan|last=Peters|date=29 April 2018|accessdate=11 May 2018}}
* The Russo Brothers wanted Steve Rogers' phone number (678-136-7092) to work in real life and redirect to a fake voicemail from the character. They couldn't do it because of the intervention of the film's affiliated legal department.{{cite|ref=true|refname=Huffpost|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/saddest-death-avengers-infinity-war_us_5af9dc8de4b0200bcab7d3e0|title=What You Missed About The Saddest Death In 'Avengers: Infinity War'|work=Huffington Post|first=Bill|last=Bradley|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}
* A scrapped idea for the rescue of Doctor Strange from Ebony Maw had Tony send his [[Iron Man Armor MK L (Earth-199999)|Iron Man Armor MK L]] onto Strange to protect him, with the armor forming itself around the [[Eye of Agamotto (Knowledge)|Eye of Agamotto]] and using it as its power source. In turn, Tony would have donned the [[Cloak of Levitation]]. The idea behind this concept was to switch the heroes' power sets to explore new interactions between the characters.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cbr.com/iron-strange-armor-avengers-infinity-war/|title=Iron Strange: Infinity War Nearly Introduced the Best Iron Man Armor of All|work=CBR.com|first=L.D.|last=Nolan|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=21 November 2019}}
** According to filmmaker [[Kevin Smith]], this scene was actually filmed, with writers Markus and McFeely having showed him set photos of {{WP|Benedict Cumberbatch}} in the Iron Man Armor and {{WP|Robert Downey, Jr.}} wearing the Cloak of Levitation.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2020/03/13/kevin-smith-reveals-doctor-strange-in-iron-mans-armor-avengers-infinity-war-scene-filmed/|title=Kevin Smith Reveals Doctor Strange In Iron Man's Armor Avengers: Infinity War Scene Was Actually Filmed|work=ComicBook.com|first=Spencer|last=Perry|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020}}
* [[James Rhodes (Earth-199999)|War Machine]] was originally going to wear two suits in this movie. This ultimately got narrowed down to one armor, which combined the best elements of the two into one.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://screenrant.com/avengers-infinity-war-machine-original-role/|title=War Machine Was Intended To Have A Bigger Role In Infinity War|work=Screen Rant|first=Cooper|last=Hood|date=8 November 2018|accessdate=13 January 2020}}
* An early idea for [[Thor Odinson (Earth-199999)|Thor]]'s journey took inspiration from the character's mythical roots, having him fight the [[Midgard Serpent]] to obtain [[Stormbreaker]]. According to McFeely, the initial approaches to Thor's mission were "much too adventure-related, and insufficiently character-based."{{cite|ref=true|refname=VF|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/07/avengers-endgame-captain-america-head-tony-stark-smart-hulk-thor-sdcc-russos-markus-mcfeely|title=Avengers: Endgame Filmmakers Reveal Dark, Trippy Original Version at Comic-Con|work=Fanity Fair|first=Joanna|last=Robinson|date=19 July 2019|accessdate=20July 2019}}
* The original script for this film had [[Peter Quill (Earth-199999)|Star-Lord]] fail to bring himself to try to kill [[Gamora (Earth-199999)|Gamora]]. The scene was revisited after receiving input from Star-Lord's actor Chris Pratt and {{sl|Guardians of the Galaxy (film)}} director [[James Gunn]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/adambvary/avengers-infinity-war-ending-explained-spoilers?utm_term=.toyLoJ9b8#.ahPe1koxl|title=Your Burning Questions About "Avengers: Infinity War," Answered|work=BuzzFeed News|first=Adam|last=Vary|date=2 May 2018|accessdate=9 May 2018}}
* [[Drax (Earth-199999)|Drax]]'s line asking, "Why is Gamora?" during the stand-off between Iron Man and Star-Lord was brought up by his actor, {{WP|Dave Bautista}}, himself.<ref name="Yahoo"/>
* In an early version of the movie's plot, Bruce Banner would have evolved into "Smart Hulk" during the battle in [[Wakanda]].{{cite|ref=true|refname=NYT|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/movies/avengers-endgame-questions-and-answers.html|title=‚ÄòAvengers: Endgame‚Äô: The Screenwriters Answer Every Question You Might Have|work=The New York Times|first=Dave|last=Itzkoff|date=29 April 2019|accessdate=3 May 2019}} Before merging, Banner and Hulk would have had a confrontation in a metaphysical mindscape taking the form of the gladiator arena from ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]''. After this encounter, the two characters would have come out merged. The fusion would have taken place during Banner's confrontation against Cull Obsidian, with the merged Hulk busting out of the [[Iron Man Armor MK XLVIII (Earth-199999)|Hulkbuster 2.0]]. This plot resolution was scrapped late into development, which caused scenes from the first act of {{sl|Avengers: Endgame}} to be reshot since they made use of Smart Hulk.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/avengers-endgame-writers-alternate-storylines|title=How the Avengers: Endgame Writers Made Life-and-Death Decisions|work=Vanity Fair|first=Anthony|last=Breznican|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=25 December 2019}}
* An earlier draft of the movie saw Doctor Strange pushing Thanos through time and space in a surreal sequence to have him judged by the [[Living Tribunal (Multiverse)|Living Tribunal]]. According to Markus, the idea was scrapped because, "We were in the middle of a really fast-paced fight, so to stop it for an LSD trip kind of sucked the air out of it."<ref name="VF"/>
* According to James Gunn, Groot's final words before dying meant "Dad."{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.cbr.com/avengers-infinity-war-groot-final-words-meaning/|title=James Gunn Reveals [SPOILER'S] Final Words in Avengers: Infinity War|work=CBR.com|first=Ian|last=Cardona|date=6 May 2018|accessdate=9 May 2018}} Co-director Anthony Russo has confirmed the script did include what Groot's final words meant.<ref name="Huffpost"/>
* The final moments of Spider-Man's death scene were improvised by {{WP|Tom Holland}}, namely the repeated blubbering of the line, "I don't want to go."{{cite|ref=true|url=https://nerdist.com/avengers-infinity-war-tom-holland-improvised-spider-man/|title=Tom Holland Improvised That AVENGERS: INFINITY WAR Scene|work=Nerdist|first=Michael|last=Walsh|date=2 May 2018|accessdate=9 May 2018}}
* In an earlier draft for this film and its sequel, Thanos snapping his fingers didn't happen until the second film. This was changed because "it would feel more like a cliffhanger than we intended" according to co-writer Christopher Markus.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/27/movies/screenwriters-avengers-infinity-wars.html|title=Screenwriters Talk Shop: How to Get Audiences to Return for Part 2|work=New York Times|first=Sopan|last=Deb|date=27 May 2018|accessdate=27 May 2018}}
* The Russo Brothers confirmed that characters like [[Elizabeth Ross (Earth-199999)|Betty Ross]] and [[Sif (Earth-199999)|Lady Sif]] died off-screen due to Thanos' finger snap, while others such as [[Howard Duckson (Earth-199999)|Howard the Duck]], [[Maybelle Parker (Earth-199999)|Aunt May]] and [[Nakia (Earth-199999)|Nakia]] survived. They refused to confirm the status of some characters because the information was deemed to be "too spoilery." These characters include [[Jane Foster (Earth-199999)|Jane Foster]], [[Edward Leeds (Earth-199999)|Ned Leeds]], [[Shuri (Earth-199999)|Shuri]], [[Korg (Earth-199999)|Korg]] and [[Miek (Earth-199999)|Miek]].{{cite|ref=true|url=http://collider.com/infinity-war-who-died-offscreen/|title=‚ÄòAvengers: Infinity War‚Äô Directors Confirm Who Lived or Died Offscreen|work=Collider|last=Keene|first=Allison|date=14 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018}} ''Avengers: Endgame'' would later reveal that Ned Leeds and Shuri were snapped, while Korg and Miek survived. Jane Foster's status remained unknown, and while the Russos confirmed Aunt May to have survived, {{sl|Spider-Man: Far From Home}} establishes she did not.

